Shan Wang 2024

Unlocking Cognitive Modeling (Human-like AI)

Making Cognitive Models Easier to Learn and Build

Learning cognitive modeling and building human-like AI models are hard. Students struggled a lot and gave up half way. In this research study, This interview study aims to understand comprehensively the pain points in the journey of learning the cognitive sciences and programming knowledge, as well as building the human-like AI models using related tools. I then provide actionable recommendations to help ease the journey.

Method

Interview

My role

Principal Investigator

Timeline

1 semester

Background

Do you know that some researchers build human-like AI? They are called cognitive modelers, simulating human problem-solving and mental processing in computerized models. ACT-R is one of the cognitive architectures about how human cognition works.

We can’t always send users over and test our products, especially in dangerous situations. Those ACT-R models simulating human cognition and behavior can help us discovering problems in driving and flying. However, not many researchers in the field because of the learning curves of related knowledge and tools.

I conduct an interview study to have a comprehensive understanding of the pain points in the journey of learning ACT-R and building/suing the models.

Goals ✨ and Questions

Explore the difficulties encountered in the journey of learning and using human-like AI model ACT-R

Provide actionable recommendations to improve user experience and accelerate engagement

Methods

Interviews with cognitive modelers

Recruitment and Process

n = 6

Criteria: any experience with ACT-R, including those who are currently learning

Insights

Update the tutorials ✅

Cognitive modeling is a field requires both cognitive science knowledge and computer science knowledge. Users are mostly self taught and use the tutorials downloaded together with the ACT-R application. Firstly, there should be more guidance on how to build the model to fill the gap between theory and practices. Secondly, the tutorials could be more organized to suit segmented learners with background from cognitive science/psychology and computer science. Thirdly, the tutorials could provide correct answers to the practice problems as hints of feedback.

Redesign a more user friendly debugger ⭐️

Users mentioned that they can draft their human-like AI model within one or weeks but take months debugging. Some users quit their graduate program for not finishing their model within two years. The bug can be as small as a typo. A more user friendly debugger with clear error warning would be very helpful. It can check the syntax grammar, help locate the potential typo, and provide hints of how to make corrections.

Build an online community 😄

All users, especially users from Japan, had reported that they lack help and support during the journey, because the resources is likely passed through “apprentice”. They can also feel intimidated to bother “big names”. Building an online community would help new users learn and ask questions. The community supports will also help them to go further in the journey.

Conclusions

Learning and building human-like AI models are indeed hard. Users lack appropriate resources to learn and have limited help, not to mention community support. Improving current materials they use, redesigning current tools they use, and building an online community would help our users - the cognitive modelers.

Reflections

If I can redo the research with more time and support, I would segment the users based on their experiences. The potentially different results from the segmented groups may shed light on interesting insights.
